Nominal Drift

Where diffusion becomes discovery.

Nominal Drift is a local scientific AI workstation for materials science, corrosion, diffusion physics and crystal intelligence workflows.

Built as a hybrid system, it combines:

* LLM reasoning** for scientific dialogue and workflow orchestration
* deterministic physics engines for trusted calculations
* mechanism-aware visualisation for microstructure and diffusion behaviour
* experiment memory + retrieval for validation and comparison
* future crystal / DFT dataset workflows for structure-aware materials intelligence

This is **not a generic chatbot**.

The language model is the reasoning layer.
**The science lives in the tools.**

Every numerical result is generated through explicit modules:

* diffusion solvers
* sensitization models
* heat-treatment workflows
* experiment databases
* dataset pipelines
* report generators

The goal is simple:

> Ask scientific questions in natural language and receive physically grounded outputs.

From chromium depletion in stainless steels to future crystal diffusion and DFT-assisted workflows, Nominal Drift is being built as a local-first scientific copilot.

---

Current Capabilities

Materials & Corrosion Workflows

* 1D Fick diffusion engine (Crank–Nicolson)
* chromium / carbon / nitrogen diffusion workflows
* sensitization and depletion studies
* engineering narration via local LLM
* static and animated visual outputs
* experiment database
* CLI and GUI orchestration (in progress)

Crystal Intelligence Lane (Phase 2 / in progress)

* MP-20
* MPTS-52
* Perov-5
* Carbon-24
* CIF-based public crystal repositories
* normalization and indexing pipelines

---

Grounded In

Nominal Drift is built on experimental diffusion data, classical transport theory and corrosion literature.

The current diffusion engine uses literature-validated Arrhenius constants for substitutional and interstitial diffusion in Fe–Cr–Ni austenitic systems.

Chromium diffusion (substitutional)

Primary reference currently used:

* Perkins, Padgett & Tunali (1973)
  *Tracer diffusion of Fe and Cr in Fe-17 wt% Cr-12 wt% Ni austenitic alloy
  *Metallurgical Transactions, 4(12), 2535–2540
  DOI: 10.1007/BF02644258

Canonical values used in the model:

* D₀ = 3.6 × 10⁻⁴ m²/s**
* Q = 272 kJ/mol**

This remains the main diffusion reference for Cr transport in the 18-8 / 316L composition space.

Carbon diffusion (interstitial)

Current C diffusivity constants are built from:

* Tibbetts (1980)
* Goldschmidt (1967)
* Smith (1990)

These support sensitization and grain-boundary depletion workflows.

Nitrogen diffusion

Nitrogen diffusion constants currently reference:

* Jack (1951)
* Grabke (1996)
* Frisk (1991)

Used for future nitride-driven HT and corrosion workflows.

Numerical foundation

The transport solver is built on:

* Fick’s Second Law
* Arrhenius diffusion formalism
* Crank–Nicolson finite difference method

Validated against:

* Crank, The Mathematics of Diffusion (1975)
* Borg & Dienes (1988)

This project is intentionally developed as a living scientific workspace —
part validated physics, part evolving toolchain, part experimental notebook.

